===Etymology===
{{calque|en|fr|danse du ventre}}, equivalent to {{af|en|belly|dance}}. First attested in English in 1889, in an article about that year's Exposition Universelle in Paris in the November 22 edition of the Yorkshire Factory Times: "A café in the Rue du Caire attracted 2,000 spectators daily to see the ‘belly dance’, and realised a total of 400,000 francs."<ref name=":0">Hawthorn, Ainsley (May 2019). [https://www.euppublishing.com/doi/full/10.3366/drs.2019.0250 "Middle Eastern Dance and What We Call It."] ''Dance Research'' 37 (1): 1-17.</ref> Early sources also used the French term ''danse du ventre'' as-is.<ref name=":0" /><ref>Morrow, W.C. (1899). [https://books.google.ca/books?id=iSr_CgAAQBAJ&q=belly+dance#v=snippet&q=belly%20dance&f=false Bohemian Paris of Today]</ref>

